def get_dtype(dtype):
    if dtype=='uint8': return np.uint8;
    if dtype=='int8' : return np.int8;
    else:
        raise ValueError('%s is not a valid type' % dtype)

get_dtype('uint8')

In [9]:
class ArrayInfo(object):
    
    def __init__(self, avg, std, value):
        self.avg   = avg
        self.std   = std
        self.value = value

    def __str__(self):
        return "ArrayInfo{avg: %1.4f, std: %1.4f, shape: %s}" \
                % (self.avg, self.std, str(self.value.shape))
    
    def __repr__(self):
        return self.__str__()
    
ArrayInfo(777, 7.7, np.array([1,2,3]))

In [10]:
class ArrayHandle(object):
    
    def __init__(self, conn, array_id):
        self.conn = conn
        self.array_id = array_id
        self.array_info = None
        
    def IsLoaded(self):
        return (self.array_info!=None)
    
    def Load(self):
        # load the data
        try:
            sql = "select d.* from array_data d where d.id=%d" % self.array_id    
            cursor = self.conn.cursor()
            cursor.execute(sql)
            record = cursor.fetchone()

            # array attributes
            std    = record[1]
            avg    = record[2]

            # reconstruct array
            ndim   = record[3]
            dim1   = record[4]
            dim2   = record[5]
            dim3   = record[6]
            dim4   = record[7]
            dtype  = get_dtype(record[8])
            blob   = record[9]
            value  = np.array(array.array('B', blob.read()), dtype=dtype)
            if   ndim == 1: value = value.reshape((dim1,))
            elif ndim == 2: value = value.reshape((dim1,dim2))
            elif ndim == 3: value = value.reshape((dim1,dim2,dim3))
            elif ndim == 4: value = value.reshape((dim1,dim2,dim3,dim4))  
            self.array_info = ArrayInfo(avg, std, value)

        # TODO: think about this part.. 
        except odb.DatabaseError, exc:
            print(exc)
        except:
            print('some other error')
        finally:
            cursor.close()
    
    def Clear(self):
        self.array_info = None
        
    def Get(self):
        if not self.IsLoaded():
            self.Load()
        return self.array_info
    
h = ArrayHandle(conn, 1)
print(h.IsLoaded())
print(h.array_info)
h.Load()
print(h.IsLoaded())
print(h.array_info)
h.Clear()
print(h.IsLoaded())

class Player(object):
    
    def __init__(self, conn, player_id):
        
        try:
            sql = "select p.* from players p where p.id=%d" % player_id
            cursor = conn.cursor()
            cursor.execute(sql)
            record = cursor.fetchone()
            
        except odb.DatabaseError, exc:
            print(exc)
        
        finally:
            cursor.close()
        
        self.id     = record[0]
        self.name   = record[1]
        self.goals  = record[2]
        self.starts = record[3]
        self.image1 = ArrayHandle(conn, record[4])
        self.image2 = ArrayHandle(conn, record[5])
        self.image3 = ArrayHandle(conn, record[6])
        self.team_id = record[7]
    
    def __str__(self):
        result = """Player {
    name: %s
    id: %f
    goals: %d
    starts: %d
    image1: %s
    image2: %s
    image3: %s
}""" % \
        (
            self.name, 
            self.id, 
            self.goals, 
            self.starts,
            str(self.image1.array_info),
            str(self.image2.array_info),
            str(self.image3.array_info),
        )
        return result
    
    def __repr__(self):
        return self.__str__()
    
    
p = Player(conn=conn, player_id=1)
print(p)
plt.imshow(p.image1.Get().value)
p

Class for the team

In [12]:
class Team(object):
    
    def __init__(self, conn, team_id):
        
        try:
            sql = "select t.* from teams t where t.id=%d" % team_id
            cursor = conn.cursor()
            cursor.execute(sql)
            record = cursor.fetchone()
            
        except odb.DatabaseError, exc:
            print(exc)
        
        finally:
            cursor.close()
        
        self.id    = record[0]
        self.name  = record[1]
        self.wins  = record[2]
        self.loses = record[3]
        self.pic1  = ArrayHandle(conn, record[4])
        
        ## reconstruct players:
        try:
            sql = """
select p.id
from players p inner join teams t on p.teams_id=t.id
where t.id=%d""" % team_id
            cursor = conn.cursor()
            cursor.execute(sql)
            records = cursor.fetchall()
            
        except odb.DatabaseError, exc:
            print(exc)
        
        finally:
            cursor.close()
            
        self.players = [Player(conn, record[0]) for record in records]
        
    
    def __str__(self):
        result = """Team {
    name: %s
    id: %f
    wins: %d
    loses: %d
    pic1: %s
    nplayers: %d
}""" % (self.name, self.id, self.wins, self.loses, str(self.pic1.array_info), len(self.players))
        return result
    
    def __repr__(self):
        return self.__str__()
    
    
t1 = Team(conn=conn, team_id=1)
print(t1)
plt.imshow(t1.pic1.Get().value)

def SelectTeams(conn, where = ""):

    sql = """
select unique team_id 
from teams_view natural join players_view
"""
    if where != "":
        sql += "where %s" % where
        
    try:
        cursor = conn.cursor()
        cursor.execute(sql)
        records = cursor.fetchall()

    except odb.DatabaseError, exc:
        print(exc)

    finally:
        cursor.close()
        
    teams = [Team(conn, record[0]) for record in records]
    return teams

teams = SelectTeams(conn, where='team_wins > 0 and player_goals > 9')
print(teams)
